revision.text:
[[File:Ada Besinnet.png|thumb|Ada Besinnet]] '''Ada Maud Besinnet Roche''' (1890–1936) also known as '''Ada Bessinet''' was an American spiritualist [[Mediumship|medium]].<ref>Ravin, James G. (1991). ''The Wanderings Of A Literary Ophthalmologist: A. Conan Doyle, Houdini, and Ada Besinnet''. Documenta Ophthalmologica 77: 335-347.</ref><ref name="Rodger 2006">Anderson, Rodger. (2006). ''Psychics, Sensitives and Somnambules: A Biographical Dictionary with Bibliographies''. McFarland. pp. 16-17. {{ISBN|0-7864-2770-1}}</ref> ==Career==
Besinnet was known for materializing 'phantom' faces, producing voices and '[[psychic]]' lights in her séances. Psychical researchers were convinced that all her phenomena were fraudulent but some suggested she may have been in a [[Dissociation (psychology)|dissociated state]].<ref name="Rodger 2006"/> Researchers found the phantom faces suspicious, commenting that they had a strong resemblance to her own face.<ref name="Polidoro 2001">[[Massimo Polidoro|Polidoro, Massimo]]. (2001). ''Final Séance: The Strange Friendship Between Houdini and Conan Doyle''. Prometheus Books. pp. 74-111. {{ISBN|1-57392-896-8}}</ref>
Besinnet refused to sit with the magician [[Harry Houdini]].<ref>[[Fulton Oursler|Oursler, Fulton]]. (1948). ''These are Strange Tales''. John C. Winston Company. p. 192</ref> She had been exposed as a fraud by an undercover magician [[Fulton Oursler]]. During the séance he heard the medium leaving her chair, moved his shoe over the seat and discovered she was not there. Oursler in his exposure wrote that Besinnet had easily performed the phenomenon herself by getting up and moving around the room making noises. He had studied [[ventriloquism]] and stated all the voices were her own. As for the faces and lights, he suggested they were masks and observed a flashlight and, on another occasion, a rag in her hand.<ref name="Polidoro 2001"/><ref>[[Joseph Rinn|Rinn, Joseph]]. (1950). ''Searchlight on Psychical Research''. Rider and Company. pp. 273-277</ref>
Besinnet was also caught cheating by psychical researcher [[James Hewat McKenzie]]. In response, Besinnet claimed she was unconscious in her séances and had no knowledge of the events that took place.<ref>Hazelgrove, Jenny. (2000). ''Spiritualism and British Society Between the Wars''. Manchester University Press. p. 250. {{ISBN|0-7190-5559-8}}</ref> [[Hereward Carrington]] who investigated Besinnet wrote that "my own sittings with this medium left me entirely unconvinced of their genuineness."<ref name="Polidoro 2001"/>
In [[Toledo, Ohio]] the spiritualist [[Arthur Conan Doyle]] attended séances with Besinnet and claimed the faces were of his mother and nephew. Doyle endorsed her as a genuine [[Materialization (paranormal)|materialization]] medium. This was disputed by other researchers who noted Besinnet had already been caught utilizing tricks by Oursler, but Doyle had ignored the exposure.<ref name="Polidoro 2001"/> Psychical researcher [[J. Malcolm Bird]] who had attended a séance with Doyle was also skeptical and concluded "I saw these particular apparitions almost as well as well as he did... they were not sufficiently clear to be identified at all, save by a liberal contribution of desire and imagination".<ref>[[J. Malcolm Bird|Bird, J. Malcolm]]. (1924). ''My Psychic Adventures''. New York: Scientific American Publishing Company. pp. 271-272</ref>
[[James H. Hyslop]] of the [[American Society for Psychical Research]] concluded after attending 70 sittings that Besinnet was responsible for the all phenomena during the séances but her trance control was a "secondary personality".<ref>Hill, Douglas; Williams, Pat. (1965). ''The Supernatural''. Hawthorn Books. p. 127</ref>
