{{Infobox person | name = <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name --> | image = Zoe Jarman at PaleyFest 2013.jpg | alt = | caption = Jarman at PaleyFest 2013's panel for ''[[The Mindy Project]]'' | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1982|12|16|mf=y}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date†|birth date†}} --> | death_place = | nationality = [[United States|American]] | other_names = | occupation = Actress, Screenwriter | years active = 2005-present | known_for = }}
'''Zoe Anne Jarman''' (born December 16, 1982)<ref name=slate /> is an [[United States|American]] actress, comedian and writer best known for her roles on ''[[Huge (TV series)|Huge]]'' and ''[[The Mindy Project]]''.
==Early life== Jarman was raised in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], and is a 2001 graduate from [[Hillsboro High School (Tennessee)|Hillsboro High School]].
==Career== Jarman's career has mostly concentrated on comedic performances. Her best known roles are Poppy in the 2010 [[ABC Family]] series ''[[Huge (TV series)|Huge]]'',<ref name=slate>{{cite web|last1=Thomas|first1=June|title=Becoming a Character: Zoe Jarman, The Mindy Project|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2013/01/15/betsy_on_the_mindy_project_zoe_jarman_talks_getting_into_character_video.html|website=Slate|accessdate=4 January 2017|date=15 January 2013}}</ref> and Betsy Putch on the first two seasons of the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]] sitcom ''[[The Mindy Project]]''.<ref name=slate /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ausiello|first1=Michael|last2=Ausiello|first2=Michael|title=Exclusive: The Mindy Project Losing a Series Regular Ahead of Season 3|url=http://tvline.com/2014/04/30/the-mindy-project-season-3-zoe-jarman-leaving-as-betsy-putch/|website=TVLine|accessdate=4 January 2017|date=30 April 2014}}</ref> She has also made guest appearances on ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'', ''[[The Birthday Boys (TV series)|The Birthday Boys]]'', and ''[[Modern Family]]''.
Jarman is a regular performer at the [[Upright Citizens Brigade Theatre]] in [[Los Angeles]], where she has performed her multiple one-woman shows.<ref>http://losangeles.ucbtheatre.com/talent/view/8501</ref>
Jarman is also a screenwriter, and has written for the [[Comedy Central]] series ''[[Workaholics]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Workaholics: "Blood Drive"|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/workaholics-blood-drive-215976|website=avclub.com|accessdate=4 January 2017|date=4 March 2015}}</ref> and the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Master of None]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Editor|first1=Sara Boboltz Entertainment|last2=Post|first2=The Huffington|title=All Those Sexist Stories In 'Master Of None' Are Based On Real Life|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/master-of-none-on-feminism-and-sexism_us_56464f7fe4b045bf3def14b3|website=The Huffington Post|accessdate=4 January 2017|date=17 November 2015}}</ref>
